{{Infobox politician | name = Harry Braun | image = File:HB 2013 (cropped).jpg | caption = Braun in 2012 | birth_name = Harry William Braun III | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1948|11|6}} | birth_place = [[Compton, California]], U.S. | party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] | otherparty = [[Independent politician|Independent]] {{small|(2004)}} | spouse = Dorothy L. Braun | residence = [[Canton, Georgia]], U.S. | alma_mater = [[Arizona State University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])}} }}
'''Harry William Braun III''' (born November 6, 1948) is an [[Americans|American]] [[renewable energy]] consultant, researcher, and political candidate. He was a congressional nominee in [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1984#Arizona|1984]] and [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1986#Arizona|1986]], and a [[presidential campaign|presidential candidate]] in [[United States presidential election, 2004|2004]], [[United States presidential election, 2012|2012]], and [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016]]. He has published papers on the [[hydrogen economy]], [[solar power]], and [[photobiology]].
== Life and work == Braun was born November 6, 1948 in [[Compton, California]]. A graduate of [[Arizona State University]], Braun lived in Arizona for 42 years. He and his wife Dorothy now reside in [[Canton, Georgia]]. In 2002, Braun was the principal of Mesa Wind LLC, which developed [[wind turbine|wind energy]] (and [[solar energy]]) projects.{{efn | name="ppf" }}
Braun received a bachelor's degree in history and general science from [[Arizona State University]] in 1971.{{efn | name="iahe"}} Since then, he has done independent research in the fields of energy technologies and resources, photobiology, molecular biology, and protein evolution.{{efn | name="ppf" | {{cite web|url=http://phoenixprojectfoundation.us/News.html|title=Harry Braun, Chairman and Senior Scientist|work=Phoenix Project Foundation|accessdate=20 August 2015}} }} Braun is an Advisory Board Member of the International Association for Hydrogen Energy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iahe.org/advisory.asp|title=Advisory Board of Directors|work=International Association for Hydrogen Energy|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref>
Braun is the founder and senior scientist of the Phoenix Project Foundation (PPF), a non-profit 501(c)(3) organization, which advocates for a [[hydrogen economy|hydrogen]]-based energy economy rather than the current [[fossil-fuel]]-based economy. The foundation promotes ideas outlined in Braun's book, ''Phoenix Project'', initially published in 1990 and revised in 2000.{{efn | name="iahe" | {{cite web|url=http://www.iahe.org/advisory.asp?did=46|title=Biography of Harry Braun, Sustainable Partners International|work=International Association for Hydrogen Energy|accessdate=20 August 2015}} }}
Braun's published papers and books include material on [[solar power]],{{efn|1992, Solar Stirling Gensets for Large-Scale Hydrogen Production.<ref>Solar Stirling Gensets for Large-Scale Hydrogen Production. ASME (American Society of Mechanical Engineers), Solar Energy Technology, Vol 13, pp. 21-31, ASME 1992.</ref>}}{{efn|1997, Stirling Energy Systems (SES): dish-Stirling program.<ref>Stirling Energy Systems (SES): dish-Stirling program. K.W.Stone, H.W.Braun, M.I.Moore, T.B.Clark; [[IEEE]] and [[McDonnell Douglas]] Electronic Systems Company, in: IECEC-97, Proceedings of the 32nd Intersociety Energy Conversion Engineering Conference, 27 Jul 1997 to 01 Aug 1997, Honolulu, HI. volume 2, pages 1039-1044, {{ISBN|0-7803-4515-0}}, DOI:10.1109/IECEC.1997.661912.[http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/login.jsp?tp=&arnumber=661912&url=http%3A%2F%2Fieeexplore.ieee.org%2Fxpls%2Fabs_all.jsp%3Farnumber%3D661912]</ref> (See also: [[Stirling Energy Systems]].) }}{{efn|1999, Status of the Boeing Dish Engine Critical Component project, 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.osti.gov/scitech/servlets/purl/3273|title=Status of the Boeing Dish Engine Critical Component Project - SciTech Connect|author=Brau, H.W.|work=osti.gov}}</ref> }} the [[hydrogen economy]],{{efn|2003, Calculating hydrogen production costs.<ref>http://evworld.com/article.cfm?storyid=502</ref>}} and [[photobiology]];{{efn|2008, Photobiology: The biological impact of sunlight on health & infection control. (See also, 1982.<ref>Quality of light held important to your health, by Kitty Maclnnis, Phoenix Gazette, November 17, 1982.</ref>) }} he has also published several versions of his book about using renewable energy to generate hydrogen, entitled ''The Phoenix Project''.{{efn|2008, The Phoenix Project: Shifting to a Solar Hydrogen Economy by 2020.<ref>The Phoenix Project: Shifting to a Solar Hydrogen Economy by 2020. Chemical Engineering & Chemical Industry Quarterly, vol. 14, No. 2, 2008, pp-107-118.[http://www.doiserbia.nb.rs/img/doi/1451-9372/2008/1451-93720802107B.pdf]</ref> (Revised version; earlier versions published in 1990),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.sl.nsw.gov.au/search~S2?/Xbraun%20phoenix&searchscope=2&SORT=D/Xbraun%20phoenix&searchscope=2&SORT=D&SUBKEY=braun+phoenix/1%2C2%2C2%2CE/frameset&FF=Xbraun%20phoenix&searchscope=2&SORT=D&1%2C1%2C|title=State Library of New South Wales /Catalogue|work=nsw.gov.au}}</ref> 2000,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Phoenix_Project.html?id=U9oOAQAAMAAJ|title=The Phoenix Project|work=google.com}}</ref><ref>"Book review (of The Phoenix Project: Shifting from Oil to Hydrogen, 2nd Edition, 2000)", by M.V.C Sastri (Dept of Energy, [[University of Madras|U.Madras]], Chennai India), published by [[Elsevier]] (in: Intl Journal of Hydrogen Energy, Volume 27, Issue 4, April 2002, Pages 465. doi:10.1016/S0360-3199(01)00129-X.[http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S036031990100129X]</ref> and 2003.<ref name="20031121npr">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1516279|title=New Energy Policy|author=[[Talk of the Nation]] interview with guests Harry Braun and [[Vijay Vaitheeswaran]]|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=November 21, 2003}}</ref>) }}
==Political campaigns== Braun has not been elected to office, but was the nominee of the Democratic party for two congressional races in the 1980s.
===Congressional campaigns=== In [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1984#Arizona|1984]], Braun was the Democratic nominee for Congress in the [[Arizona's 1st congressional district|1st congressional district of Arizona]], losing to incumbent Republican congressman [[John McCain]].<ref>"McCain, Braun vie for House seat", by Susan Turley, Tempe Daily News, October 14, 1984, page 1 and A4.</ref><ref>"McCain vs, Braun", by Susan Turley, Tempe Daily News, October 23, 1984, page A3.</ref><ref>"Braun outlines plan for energy mecca", by [unknown], Tempe Daily News, page 3, September 19, 1984</ref> According to ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'', "A key element of Braun's energy platform is what he calls the 'Phoenix Project,' a plan to mass produce hydrogen with electrolysis by using solar power to produce the electricity."<ref>"Candidate seeks to halt 'suicide' energy policy: Urges moratorium on atomic weapons to foster research", by Joel Nilsson, The Arizona Republic, September 19, 1984</ref> Major political problems of the 1980s that the plan could conceivably address included nuclear weapons, pollution, energy scarcity, and deficit spending.<ref>"The World According to Braun", by Doug MacEachern, The New Times, page 3, September 26, 1984.</ref> Braun received 22% of the vote.<ref>{{cite book|title=Statistics of the Presidential and Congressional Election of November 6, 1984|year=1985|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|location=Washington}}</ref>
In [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1986#Arizona|1986]], Braun ran again, and was again the Democratic nominee for Arizona's 1st congressional district, losing to Republican nominee [[John Jacob Rhodes III|Jay Rhodes]].<ref name = "1986 stats">{{cite news|url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/1986election.pdf|title=Statistics of the Congressional Election of November 4, 1986|work=Government Printing Office|accessdate=24 August 2015}}</ref> Energy policy in general, and [[solar power]] plus the [[hydrogen economy]] in particular, was again a key platform-plank of Braun's campaign.<ref>"Candidate serious on energy issues", by Max Jennings (Executive Editor), The Mesa Tribune, page A7, May 7, 1986.</ref><ref>"1st District candidate says solar energy only answer", by Adrianne/Adrian Flynn, Tempe Daily News, June 3, 1986.</ref><ref>"District 1 Democrat finds hope in hydrogen", Adrian/Adrianne Flynn, The Mesa Tribune, Vol. 38, No. 202, page 1, August 19, 1986</ref><ref>"Sunshine Man: Braun hopes solar solution stirs District 1 voters", by Don Harris, The Arizona Republic, August 22, 1986, page B1 (Valley & State).</ref> Braun also campaigned on a broader set of issues during October 1986, including irrigation and [[Water use#Sectoral distributions of withdrawn water use|water-use policy]].<ref>"Braun broadens appeal, shows promise in District 1 race", by Adrianne/Adrian Flynn, The Mesa Tribune, October 6, 1986.</ref><ref>"Braun says energy is not his only issue in House campaign", by [unknown], The Arizona Republic (Special Edition), October 10, 1986.</ref><ref>"1st District contest heats up after debate", by Adrianne/Adrian Flynn, The Mesa Tribune, October 20, 1986.</ref><ref>"Braun levels attack on Rhodes over CAP", by [unknown], The Arizona Republic, October 24, 1986. page B1 (Valley & State).</ref><ref>"Braun blasts CAP as welfare for rich", Stephen Higgins, Scottsdale Progress, October 23, 1986.</ref> Braun improved on his 1984 performance, and received 29% of the vote.<ref name= "1986 stats" />
===Presidential campaigns===
====2004==== In 2004, Braun ran an independent campaign for [[President of the United States|President]], with the campaign-slogan of "Making America Energy Independent & Pollution Free with Windship Hydrogen Production Systems."<ref name=wapo2004>{{cite news|last1=Achenbach|first1=Joel|title=A Show of Hands|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2004/01/13/a-show-of-hands/bf185f6d-e1d3-4d02-90f1-75d47356b957/|accessdate=26 August 2015|work=Washington Post|date=13 January 2014|quote=...turned out to be a ballot with easy-on, easy-off access. Essentially anyone could join the fun. Among those running is Harry Braun (no relation to [Carol Moseby Braun] the former senator), the only candidate whose slogan is "Making America Energy Independent & Pollution-Free with Windship Hydrogen Production Systems." "I'm talking about making the hydrogen from water," Braun said in a phone interview Sunday. "President Bush wants to make it from coal and nuclear power. That's not clean hydrogen, that's filthy hydrogen, and that's nonrenewable hydrogen." The Braun plan is to build "windships," which he describes as 500 to 1,000 feet tall, with the "hull" anchored under the sea just off the coast. A large mast would hold wind turbines. A crew, below water, would run the machinery to convert ocean water to liquid hydrogen. Each windship would cost $10 million. How many of these enormous windships would Braun need? "About a million," he said. The project would cost $6 trillion total, in his estimation. ... }}</ref> Braun's energy policy was distinct from the [[hydrogen economy]] proposed by [[George W. Bush]], in that Braun wanted to generate hydrogen from seawater via electrolysis (using [[renewable energy]]), as opposed to generating hydrogen from coal and [[nuclear power]] plants.<ref name=wapo2004 /> Braun participated in a Presidential Candidates Forum in 2004 in New Hampshire that was covered by [[C-Span]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.c-span.org/video/?179804-1/lesserknown-presidential-candidates-forum |title=Lesser-Known Presidential Candidates' Forum |author=hosted by [[List of New Hampshire state agencies#C|The New Hampshire Political Library]]<!-- methinks this is at [[St. Anselm College]] --> |publisher=[[C-SPAN]] |date=January 8, 2004 |quote=Fifteen presidential and two vice presidential candidates spoke... }}</ref>
====2012==== Braun did not run in 2008, but did run again in 2012, against incumbent Democratic President [[Barack Obama]].<ref name=DesMoinesRegister>{{cite news|last1=Clayworth|first1=Jason|title=Candidate highlights Trig Palin's Down syndrome at soapbox|url=http://caucuses.desmoinesregister.com/2011/08/19/democrat-highlights-trigg-palin-at-soapbox/|accessdate=26 August 2015|work=[[Des Moines Register]]|date=19 Aug 2011}}</ref><ref name=philly>{{cite news|last1=Cohan|first1=William D.|title=A movement or a street fair?|url=http://articles.philly.com/2011-10-11/news/30267010_1_protester-wall-street-bankers|accessdate=26 August 2015|work=[[philly.com]]|date=11 October 2011|quote=...New York Times columnist, made an unlikely comparison of Zuccotti Park to Egypt's Tahrir Square, bestowing on Occupy Wall Street a degree of gravitas it doesn't yet have. Kristof was in Tahrir Square during the protests and is a first-rate reporter, but it's difficult to believe the laconic, idiosyncratic scene on display in Manhattan bears the slightest resemblance to what occurred in Cairo. There, people were fighting for their freedom. Zuccotti Park seemed more like a low-energy street fair in desperate need of funnel cake and grilled sausages than the world-changing movement Kristof imagines it to be. '''91 percent.''' At a corner of the park were some large artworks from the Beehive Design Collective, a rural Maine artist colony. Just inside the park, one could catch the dulcet tones of Harry Braun. The white-haired chairman and senior scientist for the Phoenix Project Foundation, which is dedicated to making sure people understand the consequences of unchecked growth, is running for president of the United States. In a real democracy, Braun said, "instead of raising the national debt limit, the U.S. Congress would be instructed by the majority of citizens to cancel the tax cuts for the wealthiest Americans and any further secret banker bailouts," and return tax rates on the wealthiest Americans to 91 percent, as they were during the Eisenhower and Kennedy administrations. Good luck with the campaign, Harry! Near Braun, a young, bearded fellow was... }}</ref> Braun's 2012 campaign included stops in Iowa.<ref name=DailyIowan>{{cite news|last1=Trevick|first1=Brittany|title=Obama challenger Harry Braun in Iowa City this week|url=http://www.dailyiowan.com/2011/07/25/Metro/24295.html|accessdate=26 August 2015|work=Daily Iowan|date=25 July 2011}}</ref>
====2016==== Braun ran for the Democratic nomination again in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fec.gov/fecviewer/CandidateCommitteeDetail.do?&tabIndex=3&electionYr=2014&candidateCommitteeId=P60007630#3|title=Committee/Candidate Details|work=fec.gov}}</ref>
====2020==== Braun announced his candidacy for the Democratic nomination again in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fec.gov/data/committee/C00662247/|title=Committee/Candidate Details|work=fec.gov}}</ref>
===Proposed constitutional amendment=== Braun has proposed an amendment to the [[United States Constitution]] which he calls the Democracy Amendment. It reads "We the People, hereby empower the majority of American citizens to approve all laws, federal legislation, presidential executive orders, and judicial decisions that impact the majority of citizens." His plan is for the amendment to be ratified directly by voters through constitutional conventions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.democracyamendmentusa.net/|title=Home page|work=Democracy Amendment USA|accessdate=26 August 2015}}</ref> He has made this amendment a focus of past presidential campaigns.<ref name = "DesMoinesRegister" /><ref>Editorial, "Candidate's call for more direct democracy should be heeded," The Daily Iowan, University of Iowa, Iowa City, Iowa, Thursday, July 28, 2011: [http://dailyiowan.lib.uiowa.edu/DI/2011/di2011-07-28.pd]</ref>
