{{POV|date=June 2012}}
'''John Major Jenkins''' (1964 – 2 July 2017)<ref>{{cite LAF|id=n95-11019}}</ref> was an American author and independent researcher. He is best known for his works that theorize certain [[astronomical]] and esoteric connections of the [[Maya calendars|calendar systems]] used by the [[Maya civilization]] of [[pre-Columbian]] [[Mesoamerica]]. His writings are particularly associated with [[2012 millenarianism]] and the development of [[Mayanism]] in contemporary and popular culture, as an outgrowth from the [[New Age]] milieu<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.simonandschuster.co.uk/authors/John-Major-Jenkins/410050010|title=John Major Jenkins|website=Simon & Schuster|language=en|access-date=2017-12-19}}</ref>. He is one of the principal people who have promoted the idea that the ancient [[Maya calendar]] ends on 21 December 2012 and this portended major changes for the Earth{{vague|date=June 2012}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jsonline.com/entertainment/movies/43132752.html|title=Did the ancient Mayans predict the end of the world? |last=Dudek |first=Duane |date=April 18, 2009|work=Milwaukee Wisconsin Journal Sentinel |accessdate=2009-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9806E6D71E3FF932A35754C0A9619C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=4|title=The Final Days|last=ANASTAS|first=BENJAMIN |date=July 1, 2007|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|pages=4–6|accessdate=2009-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/06/books/06book.html|title=The End Is Near! Now the Good News: It Could Be Groovy |last=GARNER |first=DWIGHT |date= February 5, 2009 |publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-04-28}}</ref> He has self-published a number of books through his Four Ahau Press.
He died on 2 July 2017 from cancer of the kidney at the age of 53.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.letterpressdepot.com/news/2017/8/12/in-memory-of-john-major-jenkins|title=In memory of John Major Jenkins|work=Letterpress Depot|access-date=2017-12-19|language=en-US}}</ref>
==Alternative view of cosmology== {{BLP primary sources|date=June 2012}} Jenkins considered scientific approaches to [[cosmology]] a byproduct of limited thinking. In ''Tzolkin: Visionary Perspectives and Calendar Studies,'' he writes, "I primarily wish to promote a visionary approach to these matters, as there is much more to the Sacred Calendar than can be seen with the rational intellect," and that these visionary perspectives "can more closely touch the spirit of the calendar" than does the anthropological literature.<ref name=Tzolkin>{{cite book|last=Jenkins|first=John Major|title=Tzolkin: Visionary perspectives and calendar studies|year=1994|publisher=Borderland Sciences Research Foundation|isbn=0945685165}}</ref>{{rp|5}}
Jenkins also maintained that, in order to accept and understand his cosmological theories, one must also accept the premise that the Mayan kings journeyed to “distant places,” and continuously “renewed” their kingdoms at specific points in the [[Maya calendar]].<ref name=JenkinsCosmo>{{cite book|last=Jenkins|first=John Major|title=Maya cosmogenesis 2012 : the true meaning of the Maya calendar end-date|year=1998|publisher=Bear|location=Santa Fe, NM|isbn=1879181487}}</ref>{{rp|322}} Jenkins is also a supporter of “The Lost Star” theory<ref>{{cite book|last=Cruttenden|first=Walter|title=Lost star of myth and time|year=2005|publisher=St. Lynns Press|location=Pittsburgh, PA|isbn=978-0-9767631-1-6}}</ref> which extrapolates the existence of a binary companion of the Earth’s sun based on a believed mathematical discrepancies in “earth wobble.”<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alignment2012.com/thoughtsoncpak-sent-to-heidi5-24.html|title=The Great Year and the Lost Star by John Major Jenkins, May 2006|website=www.alignment2012.com}}</ref>
==Appearances== In October of the year 2000, Jenkins work was featured on two episodes of ''Places of Mystery'' series on the ''Discovery Channel''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alignment2012.com/about_jmj.html|title=About John Major Jenkins|website=alignment2012.com}}</ref>
Jenkins was interviewed and appears in the film ''Manifesting the Mind'' a film by Andrew Rutajit, executive producer of Bouncing Bear Films.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}
Jenkins is featured speaking in the documentary ''2012: Science or Superstition''. The film explores the interpretations of the ancient Mayan predictions by researchers and scholars.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RRqW_C0TBus|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref>
Jenkins is also featured in the documentary/film ''2012: Startling New Secrets''.<ref>[http://www.syfy.com/2012/investigators.php John Major Jenkins | Investigators | 2012: Startling New Secrets | Syfy<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101206003414/http://www.syfy.com/2012/investigators.php |date=December 6, 2010 }}</ref>
==Publications== *''Journey to the Mayan Underworld'' (Four Ahau Press, Boulder, CO: 1989) *''Mirror in the Sky'' (Four Ahau Press, 1991) *''Tzolkin: Visionary Perspectives and Calendar Studies'' (Borderland Sciences Research Foundation, Garberville, CA: 1992/1994) *''Mayan Sacred Science'' (Four Ahau Press, Boulder, CO: 1994) *''Maya Cosmogenesis 2012'' (Bear & Company, Santa Fe, NM: 1998) *''Galactic Alignment: The Transformation of Consciousness According to Mayan, Egyptian, and Vedic Traditions'' (Inner Traditions International (Rochester, VT) 2002) *''Pyramid of Fire'', co-authored with Marty Matz, Bear & Company, 2004 *''The 2012 Story: The Myths, Fallacies, and Truth Behind the Most Intriguing Date in History'' (Tarcher/Penguin 2009)
