==Former trustees== The [[British Museum Act 1753]] established a 42 strong Board of Trustees, which included two representatives each of the Sloane, Cotton, and Harley families, elected representatives and the following ex-officio: Archbishop of Canterbury, Lord Chancellor, Speaker of the House of Commons, Lord President of the Council, First Lord of the Treasury, Lord Privy Seal, Lord High Admiral, Lord Steward, Lord Chamberlain, the three Principal Secretaries of State, Bishop of London, Chancellor of the Exchequer, Lord Chief Justice King's Bench, Master of the Rolls, Lord Chief Justice Common Pleas, Attorney General, and Solicitor General.<ref>[https://www.britishmuseum.org/pdf/2.pdf The British Museum chapter 2]</ref>
This rose to 50 by the mid-1800s, including the addition of a trustee appointed by the Crown ([[British Museum Act 1832]]) and one representative each from the Towneley, Elgin, and Knight families.<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=45210 Walford, E 1878 Old and New London vol.4 chapter 38]</ref>
The [[British Museum Act 1963]] reduced the number of trustees to the current 25 and set the time-limit on appointments.
