{{Infobox writer | name = Mary Livermore | embed = | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = Mary Livermore.jpg | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|1820|12|19}} | birth_place = [[Boston, Massachusetts]], U.S. | death_date = {{death date and age|1905|5|23|1820|12|19}} | death_place = [[Melrose, Massachusetts]] | resting_place = | occupation = [[journalist]], [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionist]], advocate of [[women's rights]] | language = | nationality = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | notableworks = ''My Story Of The War'' | spouse = {{marriage|Daniel P. Livermore|1845}} | relations = | partner = | children = | years_active = | module = | signature = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} --> | portaldisp = <!-- "on", "yes", "true", etc; or omit --> }} [[Image:Mary livermore house melrose.JPG|240px|thumb|right|Mary Livermore House in Melrose, MA]] '''Mary Livermore''', born '''Mary Ashton Rice''', (December 19, 1820 &ndash; May 23, 1905) was an American [[journalist]], [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionist]], and advocate of [[women's rights]].
When the [[American Civil War]] broke out, she became connected with the [[United States Sanitary Commission]], headquarters at [[Chicago]], performing a vast amount of labor of all kinds—organizing auxiliary societies, visiting hospitals and military posts, contributing to the press, answering correspondence, and other things incident to the work done by that institution. She was one of those that helped organize the great fair in 1863, at Chicago, when nearly US$100,000 was raised, and for which she obtained the original draft of the [[Emancipation Proclamation]] from [[President Lincoln]], which was sold for $3,000.{{sfn|Hurd|1890|p=215-216}}
When the war was over she instituted a paper called the ''Agitator'', which was afterwards merged in the ''Woman's Journal''. Of this, she was editor for two years and a frequent contributor thereafter. On the lecture platform, she had a remarkable career, speaking mostly in behalf of [[women's suffrage]] and the temperance movements. Many years, she traveled {{convert|25000|miles}} annually, speaking five nights each week for five months of the year.{{sfn|Hurd|1890|p=215-216}}
Her printed volumes included: ''Thirty Years Too Late,'' first published in 1847 as a prize temperance tale, and republished in 1878 ; ''Pen Pictures; or, Sketches from Domestic Life'', ''What Shall We Do with Our Daughters? Superfluous Women, and Other Lectures'', ''My Story of the War. A Woman's Narrative of Four Years' Personal Experience as Nurse in the Union Army, and in Relief Work at Home, in Hospitals, Camps and at the Front during the War of the Rebellion''. For ''Women of the Day'', she wrote the sketch of the sculptress, Miss Anne Whitney; and for the ''Centennial Celebration of the First Settlement of the Northwestern States, at Marietta, Ohio, July 15, 1788'', she delivered the historical address.{{sfn|Hurd|1890|p=215-216}}
==Early years and education== Mary Ashton Rice was born in [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]] on December 19, 1821 to Timothy Rice and Zebiah Vose (Ashton) Rice.<ref name= ERA>Edmund Rice (1638) Association, 2010. Descendants of Edmund Rice: The First Nine Generations. (CD-ROM)</ref><ref name= ANB>{{cite web| last = Perry| first = Marilyn Elizabeth| title = Livermore, Mary| work = American National Biography Online| publisher = Oxford University Press| date = 2000| url = http://www.anb.org/articles/15/15-00415.html }}</ref> She was a direct descendant of [[Edmund Rice (1638)|Edmund Rice]], an early [[Puritan]] immigrant to [[Massachusetts Bay Colony]].<ref name= ERA /> Livermore came from a military family: her father fought in the [[War of 1812]] and her mother was a descendant of Captain Nathaniel Ashton of London.<ref name="auto">{{cite book|last=Holland|first=Mary G.|title=Our Army Nurses: Stories from Women in the Civil War|location=Roseville|publisher=Edinborough|ISBN=9781889020044|page=165}}</ref> Livermore was incredibly intelligent, graduating from Boston public schools at age 14.<ref name="auto"/> Because there were no public high school or college options for women of that time, she attended [[Charlestown Female Seminary (Massachusetts)|school]] at an all-[[female seminary]] in [[Charlestown, Massachusetts|Charlestown]], [[Massachusetts]], and read the entire [[Bible]] every year until the age of 23.
==Career== After graduating from the seminary in 1836, she stayed there as a teacher for two years. In 1839, she started a job as a tutor on a Virginia plantation, and after witnessing the cruel institution of [[slavery]], she became an abolitionist. She also began work with the [[temperance movement]] at this time, identified with the Washington Temperance Reform and an editor for a juvenile temperance paper.<ref name="auto"/> In 1842, she left the plantation to take charge of a private school in [[Duxbury, Massachusetts]], where she worked for three years. She also taught at [[Charlestown, Massachusetts]].{{sfn|Hurd|1890|p=215-216}}
She married Daniel P. Livermore, a [[Universalist Church of America|Universalist]] minister in May 1845,<ref name= ANB /> and in 1857, they moved to [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]]. In that year, her husband established the ''New Covenant'', a Universalist journal of which she became associate editor for twelve years, during which time she frequently contributed to periodicals of her denomination and edited the ''Lily''.{{sfn|Hurd|1890|p=215-216}}
As a member of the [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] party, Livermore campaigned for [[Abraham Lincoln]] in the [[1860 presidential election]]. In the Chicago Wigwam in 1860, Livermore was the only woman reporter assigned a location for work amidst over hundreds of male reporters. She published a collection of nineteen essays entitled ''Pen Pictures'' in 1863. <ref>{{cite book|last=Holland|first=Mary|title=Our Army Nurses: Stories from Women in the Civil War|location=Roseville|publisher=Edinborough Press|page=166|isbn=9781889020044}}</ref>
=== American Civil War === During the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], she volunteered as an associate member of the [[United States Sanitary Commission]] at 40 years old.<ref name="auto1">{{Cite book|last=Tsui|first=Bonnie|title=She Went to the Field: Women Soldiers of the Civil War|location=Guilford|publisher=TwoDot|date=2006|isbn=978-0-7627-4384-1|page=115}}</ref> As agent of its Chicago branch, later named the Northwestern branch, she attended a council of the National Sanitary Commission at [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] in December 1862, organized many aid societies, visited army posts and hospitals, and in 1863, organized the North-western Sanitary Fair in Chicago which raised $86,000. President Lincoln donated his own copy of the [[Emancipation Proclamation]], which was auctioned off at $10,000. Livermore eventually became the co-director of the Chicago branch with [[Jane Hoge]], another soldier's aid advocate.<ref name="auto1"/> The two women completed a hospital inspection tour across Illinois, Kentucky, and Missouri.<ref name="auto2">{{Cite book|last=Tsui|first=Bonnie|title=She Went to the Field: Women Soldiers of the Civil War|location=Guilford|publisher=TwoDot|date=2006|isbn=978-0-7627-4384-1|page=116}}</ref> With a thorough understanding of the needs of the hospitals, Hoge and Livermore sent $1 million worth of food and supplies to hospitals and battlefields most in need.<ref name="auto2"/>
Livermore, like many other nurses, came up against the issue of women disguised as male soldiers. On a visit to the camp of the 19th Illinois Infantry, a captain pointed out a soldier to Livermore, asking if she noticed anything odd about them.<ref name="auto3">{{cite book|last=Hall|first=Richard|title=Women on the Civil War Battlefront|location=Lawrence|publisher=University Press of Kansas|page=130|isbn=9780700614370}}</ref> Livermore confirmed the captain's suspicions that the soldier was indeed a woman. The captain called the soldier for questioning, and though she pleaded to stay in service near her beloved, Livermore escorted her out of camp.<ref name="auto3"/> The soldier escaped Livermore, however, and fled.
In addition to her nursing services, Livermore was also a prolific writer. She authored numerous books of poetry, essays, and stories, and was a recognized member of the literary guild. Though Livermore had to sacrifice much of her social justice work for nursing, she still managed to publish some kind of content once a week throughout the entirety of the war.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brockett|first1=L.P.|last2=Vaughan|first2=Mary|title=Woman's Work in the Civil War: a Record of Heroism, Patriotism and Patience|location=Philadelphia|publisher=Zeigler, McCurdy and Company|year=1867|page=134}}</ref>
== Post-war life == [[File:Mary Livermore 1901.jpg|thumb|upright|Mary Livermore, 1901]] After the war, Livermore devoted herself to the promotion of [[women's suffrage]] (along with [[Lucy Stone]] and [[Julia Ward Howe]] ) and the [[temperance movement]], founding in Chicago in 1869 ''The Agitator'', which in 1870, after she moved to [[Boston]], was merged into the ''[[Woman's Journal]]'', of which she was an associate editor until 1872.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://iamwoman-mxtodis123.blogspot.com/2010/07/mary-livermore.html |title=I Am Woman: A Celebration of Womanhood |first1=Mary |last1=Livermore |accessdate=January 22, 2012}}</ref> Livermore became the first president of the Association for Advancement of Women, as well as president of [[American Woman Suffrage Association]].<ref name="auto2"/>
Like many Universalists of the time, she was interested in [[spiritualism]], and following her husband's death in 1899, she became convinced that he had communicated with her through a medium. Livermore died in [[Melrose, Massachusetts|Melrose]], Massachusetts on May 23, 1905.
==Legacy== The Mary A. Livermore School in Melrose, operational from 1891 to 1933,<ref>{{ cite web | title = Melrose|date=September 5, 1933|publisher=''[[Boston Globe|Daily Boston Globe]]''|accessdate=January 18, 2018|page=10}}</ref> was an elementary school named for Livermore. In 1943, nearly four decades after her death, she became the namesake of a [[World War II]] [[Liberty ship]], the [[SS Mary A. Livermore|SS ''Mary A. Livermore'']].
==Selected works== {{commons category|Illustrations from My Story Of The War by Mary Livermore|My Story Of The War}} * ''The Children's Army'' (1844), temperance stories. * "The Twin Sisters: or, The History of Two Families," collected in ''The Two Families; and The Duty that Lies Nearest. Prize Stories'' (1848), a temperance story. * ''A Mental Transformation'' (1848). * ''Pen Pictures'' (1863), short stories. * ''What Shall We Do With Our Daughters? and Other Lectures'' * ''[[:s:A Woman of the Century|A Woman of the Century]]'' (1893) (ed. Willard, Frances E. & Livermore, Mary A.) - online available in [[File:Wikisource-logo.svg|16px|alt=small Wikisource logo]] [[Wikisource]]. * ''My Story of the War: The Civil War Memories of the Famous Nurse, Relief Organizer and Suffragette'' (1887/1995) with Introduction by Nina Silber. New York: De Capo Press {{ISBN|0-3068-0658-4}}. * ''[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/m/moa/4728109.0001.001 The story of my life ; or, The sunshine and shadow of seventy years]'' (1897). * Cooperative Womanhood in the State.(1891) ''[[North American Review]]'' 153 pp.&nbsp;283–295.
